title: For Sale:  Rare WWII German Luftwaffe G29(O) Steyr Mauser 8mm
postcontent: G29 (O) Mauser Service Rifle 1939-1940 Steyer Production/Luftwaffe Service; 8mm MauserExtremely rare, 1939 dated, 660 coded,G.29 (O) rifle.  This short rifle was produced by Austrian legend Steyer under contract with the Third Reich's Luftwaffe.  A rare series that was manufactured only in 1938 and 1939, this example was one of the final of this model ever produced, having been assembled, presumably in Jan. 1940, of parts made in December of 1939.  The rifle has all matching and correct features, apart from a K98K replacement bolt, including the distinct swivels, full length upper handguard, milled components, apart from the barrel band.   Wafenamt 623 on all major components, andcrisply cartouched stock with the "L" cartuche denoting Luftwaffe issue.  Additionally, the guncorrectly lacks a modeldesignation on the left side wall and the serial number falls in the correct "b" range,but it is 558 rifles later than the last known weapon in this run.  In original condition, with no signs of post-war foreign service or import mark, this weapon is a fine candidate for having being brought back by a GI returning home from service in Europe.  One of an estimated 50,000 total produced, these rifles were issued exclusively to the Luftwaffw, and are considered among the rarest of the K98K family.  In very fine condition, this G29 (O) would be a superb addition to the advanced, dedicated collection.Very good condition with no sign of refinish or restoration, the majority of the finish has faded to a unifirm pewter patina on the barrel, with the receiver and bolt components at around 30% original blue.  There is no rust or deep pitting, with light pitting around the muzzle and oxidation staining prevelant on most surfaces.  Components are properly marked and all numbered parts are matching, with the exception of the bolt components, to include the furniture.  The walnut stock is well marked with the correct "L" cartouche, vivis Waffenamts, and serial number matching the gun.  In very good condition, it lacks chips, cracks, but does show scattered handling marks, pressure dents, and dings.  Mechanically excellent, the bore is correspondingly in excellent condition, having strong, well defined rifling, with traces of residue and lint, and no rust, pitting, frost, or heavy oxidation.  Includes one correct WaA623-marked muzzle cap.  $1400 firm. title: For Sale/Trade:  Kimber/CZ 30-06
postcontent: If you're interested in emailing, have the money or a good trade offer.  Also, the gun has to be picked up in Chattanooga.  I'm not going to drive an hour to meet you, hold it for you until payday, etc.Do you like murdering soft, fuzzy, yet delicious woodland creatures but your .223 doesn't put a big enough hole in them? Do you want to shoot at them from half a mile away but can't seem to knock them down with your current rifle? Try an upgrade!This is a bit of a strange gun to track down info on.  Apparently, when Kimber was sold, they bought a bunch of Mauser actions, slapped on some barrels they produced in some synthetic stocks and started off selling these to pay the bills and get on their feet.  I've also seen information on CZ doing them as well, or helping, or something.  I haven't tried TOO hard to track down the origins but it's a slick rifle and shoots well, I just don't hunt and really only shoot for fun at 100 yards max and I can't hit a thing anyways.  I can tell you it's a Swedish Mauser action with a Kimber barrel in a black synthetic stock.  It has a basic sling and comes in a plain old black zipper padded bag for carrying or storing, and has a scope that's probably a bit too small for real long range shooting.  I do have some ammo with it, but probably not tons.  I'd guesstimate I have about 20 or so North GA Reloading M1 Garand load cartridges, 30 or so Remington Core Lokt basic cartridges, and 20 or so Winchester Silver Tip cartridges.  These are approximate counts as I have all the ammo at my parent's house in Harrison and am going on memory.  I am mostly looking for trades as I don't need a big bolt gun but will listen to cash offers.  I do have a few more pics than Armslist will let me upload, so email away.

title: For Sale:  Buffalo Bill Historical Center-Winchester Museum Colt .44-40 Limited Edition Revolver and "Winchester Rider" Bronze by Bob Scriver
postcontent: This is a rare and unique offering for the descriminating collector.   In 1980 the Buffalo Bill Historical Center expanded its Winchester installation.  A large part of the funding was raised by the sale of the Special Colt and the Bob Scriver Bronze of the "Winchester Rider".   These two pieces were available seperately or could be acquired together as a "same serial number" set.  There were only a few of the pieces sold as a set.  It seems most people wanted one or the other.  It is estimated that there are fewer than ten sets with matchng serial numbers out of the 250 of each.  Charleston Heston acquired one set.  George H.W. Bush acquired a set.  One set is reportedly in a museum .  The set you see here is the fourth we are aware of.  There have been sales of the items individually since 1980 but only a few.  You can search the web for these items and the sales will appear.  The few sales were handled by major western art houses.  We have documentation from both the Colt Firearms Co. and the Buffalo Bill Historical Center.  Copies of the documentation and additional photos are available.   Please, serious inquiries only.
